// Phase 2.6 fixture #5 — Case A violation: bare Integrity, no guard.
//
// THE LOAD-BEARING DEMO FIXTURE. A function declared
// `-> Integrity | Incomplete` whose single return statement produces
// bare Integrity with no incompleteness predicate evaluated anywhere
// in the body. Every downstream caller would receive Integrity for
// every input, defeating the union-return-type contract: the
// `Incomplete` arm of the union is never reached, so the function's
// declared inability to fully process certain inputs is a false
// promise.
//
// The thesis paper §4 names this as the canonical Process-2 risk in
// return-type form. Bayyinah's `apply_scan_incomplete_clamp` enforces
// the equivalent rule at scanner level: a scanner that reports
// integrity_score=1.0 on a document it could not fully read is
// telling the reader the document displays and contains the same
// content, when in fact it did not display or contain anything
// legible to the scanner. Phase 2.6 transposes that runtime check
// into a compile-time type rule.
//
// Expected: one Case A marad naming the function (`scan_unsafely`),
// the unguarded return path, and the rule violated. Recovery options
// in the marad's minimal_fix: either add an `if not <pred>` guard,
// or change the function's declared return type to bare Integrity.

bismillah Sloppy {
    authority: NAMING_MD
    serves: purpose_hierarchy.truth_over_falsehood
    scope: scan
    not_scope: nothing_excluded
}

fn scan_unsafely(file: File) -> Integrity | Incomplete {
    return Integrity
}
